[bash:b96f0d2d] Error: Command failed: /usr/local/bin/docker exec relay-agent-b96f0d2dffab bash -c python3 /relay_tool_runner.py text_editor '{"command":"create","path":"/home/computeruse/google_stitch.md","new_file_text":"# Google Stitch\n\n## Introduction\n\nGoogle Stitch is an AI-powered creative tool developed by Google that enables users to generate and edit images using natural language prompts. Announced and released in 2025, Google Stitch is part of Google'\''s broader suite of generative AI products and is designed to streamline the process of creating visual assets — particularly user interface (UI) mockups, design components, and general-purpose images — directly from text descriptions. It leverages Google'\''s state-of-the-art image generation models to bridge the gap between ideation and visual output.\n\n---\n\n## Overview\n\nGoogle Stitch is a **text-to-image and image editing platform** built on top of Google'\''s Gemini and Imagen model families. Unlike general-purpose image generators, Stitch places a strong emphasis on **UI and product design workflows**, making it especially valuable for developers, designers, and product teams who need to quickly prototype interfaces or generate design assets without deep graphic design expertise.\n\nStitch integrates into Google'\''s AI ecosystem and is accessible via **Google AI Studio**, allowing seamless interoperability with other Google AI tools and APIs. Its core functionality revolves around generating high-fidelity images — from simple illustrations to detailed UI screens — and iterating on them using conversational, natural language instructions.\n\n---\n\n## Key Features and Capabilities\n\n### 🎨 Text-to-Image Generation\n- Generate images from plain English (or multilingual) prompts.\n- Supports a wide range of styles: photorealistic, illustrated, flat design, UI mockups, and more.\n- Powered by Google'\''s **Imagen** generative models for high-quality visual output.\n\n### 🖥️ UI / UX Mockup Generation\n- Specialised capability to generate **app screens, website layouts, and interface components** from descriptive prompts.\n- Produces design mockups that can serve as a starting point for development or further design refinement.\n- Understands UI-specific terminology (e.g., \"navigation bar\", \"card layout\", \"modal dialog\").\n\n### ✏️ Iterative Editing via Natural Language\n- Modify generated images using follow-up text instructions (e.g., \"change the button colour to blue\" or \"add a search bar at the top\").\n- Maintains context across multi-turn conversations, enabling progressive refinement.\n- Supports **in-painting** and **targeted edits** to specific regions of an image.\n\n### 🔗 Integration with Google AI Studio\n- Accessible directly through **Google AI Studio** (aistudio.google.com).\n- Works alongside other Gemini-powered tools for a unified AI-assisted workflow.\n- API access allows developers to embed Stitch capabilities into their own applications.\n\n### 📐 Style Consistency\n- Ability to maintain visual consistency across multiple generated assets (e.g., a cohesive set of app screens that share a design language).\n- Style transfer and style-locking features to ensure brand alignment.\n\n### 📤 Export and Handoff\n- Generated images can be exported in common formats (PNG, JPEG, SVG where applicable).\n- Designed with developer handoff in mind, making it easier to move from prototype to implementation.\n\n### 🌐 Multimodal Input\n- Upload existing images as references or starting points.\n- Combine image inputs with text prompts for more precise generation and editing.\n- Supports iterative workflows where users alternate between uploading and generating assets.\n\n---\n\n## Use Cases\n\n### Product and UX Design\nDesigners can rapidly prototype app screens, landing pages, and component libraries without opening traditional design tools. Stitch dramatically reduces the time between a design concept and a shareable visual artefact.\n\n### Developer Prototyping\nDevelopers who need to visualise a UI concept before writing code can use Stitch to generate realistic mockups, which can then guide front-end implementation.\n\n### Marketing and Content Creation\nMarketing teams can generate visual content — banners, social media graphics, promotional imagery — from simple text briefs, speeding up creative production cycles.\n\n### Startups and Indie Makers\nSolo founders and small teams with limited design resources can use Stitch to produce professional-looking UI designs and marketing materials without hiring a dedicated designer.\n\n### Education and Learning\nStudents and educators in design, HCI (Human-Computer Interaction), and computer science can use Stitch to explore design concepts interactively and learn how to describe visual interfaces precisely.\n\n### Accessibility Prototyping\nTeams focused on accessible design can prototype and iterate on accessible UI patterns, testing different layout and contrast options quickly.\n\n### Game and App Asset Generation\nGenerate icons, splash screens, background images, and other visual assets for games and applications at scale.\n\n---\n\n## How It Works\n\nGoogle Stitch operates through a multi-step generative pipeline:\n\n### 1. Prompt Interpretation\nThe user inputs a natural language prompt describing the desired image or UI. Google'\''s large language model (LLM) component — part of the Gemini family — parses the prompt to extract intent, style directives, layout cues, and content requirements.\n\n### 2. Image Synthesis\nThe interpreted prompt is passed to **Google'\''s Imagen model**, which generates a high-resolution image based on the described parameters. Imagen uses a **diffusion-based architecture**, progressively refining a noisy image into a coherent visual output.\n\n### 3. Contextual Editing Loop\nIf the user requests changes, Stitch maintains a **session context** that includes the original prompt, the generated image, and all subsequent modifications. This allows the model to apply targeted edits (e.g., recolour a specific element, add or remove components) without regenerating the entire image from scratch where possible.\n\n### 4. Multimodal Grounding (Optional)\nWhen the user uploads a reference image, the model uses **vision encoders** to understand the existing visual content and incorporate it into the generation or editing process — for example, matching the style of an uploaded design or building upon an existing screenshot.\n\n### 5. Output and Export\nThe final image is rendered and made available for download or further iteration within the platform. Where API access is used, the image is returned as a base64-encoded payload or a hosted URL.\n\n---\n\n## Benefits\n\n| Benefit | Description |\n|---|---|\n| **Speed** | Generate design assets in seconds rather than hours, dramatically accelerating design sprints and prototyping. |\n| **Accessibility** | Lowers the barrier to entry for visual design — no professional design skills required to produce high-quality mockups. |\n| **Iteration Velocity** | Natural language editing enables rapid iteration cycles without the friction of traditional design tooling. |\n| **Integration** | Tight integration with Google'\''s AI ecosystem (Gemini, AI Studio, Vertex AI) makes it easy to incorporate into existing workflows. |\n| **Cost Efficiency** | Reduces reliance on external design agencies or freelancers for early-stage prototyping and ideation. |\n| **Consistency** | Style-locking features help maintain visual coherence across large sets of generated assets. |\n| **Scalability** | API access enables generation at scale — useful for dynamic content pipelines that require personalised or varied visual assets. |\n| **Collaboration** | Shared sessions and exportable outputs facilitate design collaboration across distributed teams. |\n\n---\n\n## Getting Started\n\n### Prerequisites\n- A **Google account** with access to Google AI Studio.\n- Acceptance of Google'\''s Generative AI usage policies.\n- (For API access) A Google Cloud project with the relevant APIs enabled.\n\n### Step 1: Access Google AI Studio\nNavigate to [aistudio.google.com](https://aistudio.google.com) and sign in with your Google account.\n\n### Step 2: Open Stitch\nWithin AI Studio, locate the **Stitch** tool from the product navigation or tools menu.\n\n### Step 3: Write Your First Prompt\nEnter a descriptive text prompt in the input field. For example:\n```\nA clean mobile app home screen for a fitness tracking app with a dark theme, \nshowing today'\''s workout summary, a progress ring, and a bottom navigation bar.\n```\n\n### Step 4: Generate and Review\nClick **Generate** and review the output. Evaluate the layout, style, and content of the generated image.\n\n### Step 5: Iterate\nUse follow-up prompts to refine the output:\n```\nChange the colour scheme to use a deep blue and white palette.\nAdd a notification bell icon in the top right corner.\n```\n\n### Step 6: Export\nOnce satisfied, download the image in your preferred format for use in design tools, presentations, or development handoffs.\n\n### API Access (Advanced)\nFor programmatic access, enable the **Imagen API** or the **Gemini API with image generation** in your Google Cloud project and use the relevant SDK:\n\n```python\n# Example using Google'\''s Generative AI Python SDK\nimport google.generativeai as genai\n\ngenai.configure(api_key=\"YOUR_API_KEY\")\n\nmodel = genai.ImageGenerationModel(\"imagen-3.0-generate-002\")\n\nresult = model.generate_images(\n    prompt=\"A minimalist mobile banking app dashboard with a card balance view and recent transactions list\",\n    number_of_images=1,\n    aspect_ratio=\"9:16\",\n)\n\nresult.images[0].save(\"banking_ui_mockup.png\")\n```\n\nRefer to the [Google AI documentation](https://ai.google.dev) for full SDK references and API specifications.\n\n---\n\n## Pricing and Availability\n\n### Availability\n- **Google Stitch** is available through **Google AI Studio** and is part of Google'\''s broader Gemini API offering.\n- Access is currently available in **select regions**, with rollout expanding over time. Check [Google AI Studio](https://aistudio.google.com) for current regional availability.\n- The tool is available to individual developers, designers, and enterprise users.\n\n### Pricing Tiers\n\n| Tier | Access Level | Cost |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Free Tier** | Limited number of generations per day via Google AI Studio; subject to rate limits. | Free |\n| **Gemini API (Pay-as-you-go)** | Access via API with per-image pricing based on resolution and model version. | Charged per image generated (see Google AI pricing page) |\n| **Google Cloud / Vertex AI** | Enterprise-grade access with higher throughput, SLAs, data residency controls, and integration with Google Cloud services. | Custom / usage-based pricing |\n\n> **Note:** Pricing details are subject to change. Always refer to the official [Google AI pricing page](https://ai.google.dev/pricing) and [Google Cloud pricing](https://cloud.google.com/vertex-ai/pricing) for the most up-to-date information.\n\n### Free Tier Limits\n- Free tier users can generate a set number of images per day (limits vary and are updated by Google periodically).\n- Rate limits apply to prevent abuse; higher limits are available on paid tiers.\n- Free tier usage may include a Google Stitch or Gemini watermark on generated images in some configurations.\n\n### Enterprise Considerations\n- Enterprise customers using **Vertex AI** benefit from additional features including:\n  - No data usage for model training (data privacy guarantees).\n  - Higher rate limits and dedicated throughput.\n  - Access to Google Cloud'\''s compliance and security certifications (SOC 2, ISO 27001, HIPAA eligibility, etc.).\n  - Custom model fine-tuning options.\n\n---\n\n## Limitations and Considerations\n\n- **Accuracy of UI Generation:** While Stitch excels at generating visually appealing mockups, the generated UIs may not always be pixel-perfect or immediately production-ready; human design review is recommended.\n- **Text Rendering:** Like many generative image models, rendering precise text within images (e.g., labels, button text) can sometimes be imperfect.\n- **Content Policies:** Stitch adheres to Google'\''s [Generative AI Prohibited Use Policy](https://policies.google.com/terms/generative-ai/use-policy). Certain types of content cannot be generated.\n- **Regional Restrictions:** Availability may vary by country or region due to regulatory requirements.\n- **Evolving Product:** As a relatively new product, features, pricing, and capabilities are subject to rapid change.\n\n---\n\n## Related Google AI Tools\n\n| Tool | Description |\n|---|---|\n| **Google AI Studio** | The primary platform for accessing Gemini models and tools including Stitch. |\n| **Gemini API** | The underlying API powering many of Google'\''s AI features, including image generation. |\n| **Imagen** | Google'\''s dedicated text-to-image model family, which powers Stitch'\''s image generation. |\n| **Vertex AI** | Google Cloud'\''s enterprise AI platform, offering access to Imagen and other models at scale. |\n| **Project IDX** | Google'\''s AI-powered development environment, which can complement Stitch for full design-to-code workflows. |\n\n---\n\n## Further Resources\n\n- 📖 [Google AI Studio](https://aistudio.google.com) — Try Stitch directly.\n- 📄 [Google AI Developer Documentation](https://ai.google.dev/docs) — Full API references and guides.\n- 💬 [Google AI Developer Forum](https://discuss.ai.google.dev) — Community support and discussions.\n- 📰 [Google DeepMind Blog](https://deepmind.google/discover/blog/) — Research updates and announcements.\n- ☁️ [Vertex AI — Imagen on Google Cloud](https://cloud.google.com/vertex-ai/generative-ai/docs/image/overview) — Enterprise image generation documentation.\n\n---\n\n*Last updated: 2025. Information is based on Google Stitch'\''s availability and features as announced and released in 2025. Features and pricing are subject to change — always refer to official Google documentation for the latest details.*\n"}'
